I recently had a very disappointing experience at Chipotle. Not only was the food subpar, but the overall cleanliness of the place left a lot to be desired.

Firstly, the food was far from what I expected. The ingredients seemed to be of low quality and lacked freshness. The rice was dry and clumpy, the meat was overcooked and lacked flavor, and the vegetables were wilted and unappetizing. It was clear that the food was not prepared with care and attention to detail.

Additionally, the hygiene of the restaurant was a major concern. The tables were sticky and dirty, and there was a noticeable lack of cleanliness in the dining area. The floors were littered with food crumbs and the condiment station was messy and disorganized. It seemed as though the staff had not properly cleaned or maintained the restaurant.

Furthermore, the overall atmosphere was uninviting. The restaurant was dimly lit and had a stale odor. The seating was uncomfortable and the overall ambiance was far from welcoming. It was not an enjoyable place to dine in.

Overall, my experience at Chipotle was extremely disappointing. The food was of poor quality and the cleanliness of the restaurant was lacking. I would not recommend this particular Chipotle location based on my experience.

The Maserati Sebring II: Luxury That’s Still At Home Among The Skeletons Of An Old Cement Factory“The Sebring 2 is not an overtly flashy car; it’s not made to shock and awe. The people who would choose such a car would not feel that they have something to prove. On the contrary, this car was for those with a lot to spend but with little to prove in doing so. It’s for those who find no point in bragging about a life that includes a fair share of brag-worthy fodder.“This photoshoot was done in the morning, staving off the ruthless heat of the mid afternoon sun, and we are nested in shadows that coat this place in contrast. The spirit of some imagined “last night” is still here, not yet washed out by the following day. That’s the essence of this car. It skirts the line between hedonistic and no-nonsense seemingly without compromise on either end, fitting in equally well in posh valet lines as it does here among the sunbaked remains of heavy industry and hard labor.”Find the full story and gallery by Virgiliu Andone (@quicklizzard) at Petrolicious.comLink in bio#Maserati #MaseratiSebring #Barcelona #ItalianCars #ClassicCars #Petrolicious #DriveTastefully

I loved your book. Thank you for sharing yourself.

As I’ve been working my way through the book, I keep finding so many similarities/parallels to my own childhood…like a scary amount.  I’m 44 now and grew up in the Midwest - so instead of a Boston accent, my Mom degraded me with a midwestern, northern Wisconsin accent 😵‍💫🥸😆 On a more serious note, as I read through the book, so many memories of my childhood came rushing back….the feelings, the smells… that constant anxiety (my guts were always twisted up throughout my childhood for one reason or another). The homesickness for a mother who really never paid much attention to me - wanting to be near her, crying at a friends sleepover in the middle of the night. After lots of therapy and some good meds, I’m rather content with my life. I applaud your bravery.  Thank you for sharing your story.  If my mother were still alive today, she would’ve reacted EXACTLY the same as yours when your book was published and presented to her…gotta love a mom with a personality disorder and unresolved childhood trauma! 🙃 Here’s to us! Still we rise.  Thought the days aren’t always easy, we’re working through our shit and coming out stronger, more empathetic and informed people…or at least I hope so 😊. Thanks again for sharing so much of yourself with us. I’ve laughed, cried, felt all the emotions while reading your book.  Thank you for raising awareness.  Thank you for making a difference ❤️

In my heart i hope for a few things: 1) you did not decide to take your life, you had just discovered your life purpose thru a lifetime of hell 2) I just saw a 48 minute video and i know that you finally escaped your demons, not only your book says that, but the way your words are spoken, i can tell ( feel ) that is not Matt acting, that is Matt speaking from his heart and wounds. I could totally feel your pain …the tiredness… Your book is a true testament of your path as a human being who had a huge weight to carry, who lived hell despite money and success, who turned his pain into a mission to help others, to me this is a symbol of hope.  I hope you left sweetly knowing that “ it was not your fault “, and that you were able to turn your lifetime of struggle into a helping tool. You made your contribution, and I will try to use your passing as a precious memory , a guide.You were a daily guest in my home. I presented Friends to my “back then “11 year old daughter in 2020 during COVID, she fell for the show so much that we’ve started to watch it non-stop, this has created a sort of deep connection that when i heard of your passing it felt like i had lost someone in real life, that i knew in person. I know Chandler was not you but after hearing you talk on quite a few interviews i found out that the character of Chandler does deliver some of your real life traits, the main one : the desperate need to be seen and loved and the immense fear of not beingy deserving of that. In the show you found your Monica, in real life that apparently did not get fixed , and apparently your journey here ended with the same feeling that has accompanied you all life long : all alone . The only missing piece is that a spiritual light came to take you, so you were not all alone as I might think. I need to believe that people who die alone they really don’t! I also know that in this moment there are humans being killed ( i pray for those too ) but your passing touched me deeply in a way i could never imagine especially for someone i never met. with much appreciation and appreciation
You saved so many people with your talent ….. you will always be my favourite friend ❤️

Comment 😫 below if you’ve ever been nervous to post on IG because you were scared people would judge you. I’m talking about a very specific type of judgement that I feel is super counter-productive. Recently I’ve noticed an increase in judgement around how people contribute to humanity. Something tragic happens in the world and the internet becomes a brawl about who is doing what to help. On the one hand, keeping people accountable and wanting people to help causes is a good thing. We should all be doing our part. But when it goes too far, it becomes toxic. Someone donates to a cause and the response is, “that’s not enough.” Someone highlights an issue and the response is, “what about xyz.” Someone experiences an ounce of joy during tragedy and the response is, “must be nice!” I’ll be vulnerable and share that it happens to me all the time. I can literally spend an entire month raising funds for girls in need, but that effort will be dismissed in seconds because I didn’t post an IG story about another issue that I’m not as familiar with. I don’t think we should be performative.I’m not sure what the goal of this energy is. To foster a culture in which people feel nervous and hesitant to give what they can doesn’t feel productive to me. Especially because we know that most problems in the world cannot be solved by one person. Instead we should be creating a culture where service and joy go hand-in-hand. After all, service is so powerful not only because it helps others, but because it makes us feel good and helps us. Perhaps that’s why our chemical production was created this way. And if we rob it of that joy, where does that leave us? This has been on my mind a lot recently. Probably because right now I’m flying to India for the first time on behalf of @UnicornIsland Fund. And one of my personal objectives is to have two things be true at once: 1) I can be of service towards this issue I care so much about and 2) I can experience joy and laughter along the way. I encourage you to find that cause you really care about and dive in. If yours is gender equality, follow @unicornisland and join our mission. This will be a safe space x ❤️📷: @saulopez

Mumbai got me like 😁 It’s been 4 years since I’ve visited India because the pandemic cancelled all my plans in 2019. I usually visit 1-2 times a year and this has been the largest gap of not doing so in my career. Travelling is a privilege. And it’s one I prioritize working towards because I think travelling is responsible for a lot of my greatest strengths as a person. Namely, travelling so much has taught me to become adaptable and to recognize that your way, isn’t the only way. The reality is that we all grow up in a bubble, in which people talk a certain way, work a certain way, respect or disrespect people a certain way and problem solve a certain way. And it becomes very easy to think that way is the only and right way. But it’s not. And while I do strongly believe that there is much work to do in every country in the world, India included, to improve on issues like gender equality, that’s not the same as believing every part of another country or culture should operate in a way you’re familiar with. I’m used to doing business via email. This past week I learned to adapt to What’s App. I’m used to LA traffic and this past week I adapted because I experienced Mumbai traffic 😅 And I’m accustomed to alone time and slightly more personal space (a privilege in itself) but when you’re in the most populated country in the world, you have to adapt. And my favourite, I’m used to saying “yes, no or maybe” and now I’ve adapted and I have a head nod for every emotion. No words needed. We can become so used to making our surroundings suitable for us, which is a lovely luxury that people should practice if they can. I certainly do. But travelling reminds me that we also need to have the ability to adjust and pivot if the situation calls for it. And the situation often does in life, in relationships and in business. Travel is a great way to exercise that skill. And to get off your high horse a little bit and get humbled. Thank you for always welcoming me with open arms and hearts India❤️📸: @saulopez

PROTOCOLS: THE KEY TO PRODUCTIVITY  TO RELAXATION• -On the Huberman Lab podcast, we often talk about protocols. The reason for using that word as opposed to “hacks” or tools, or some other descriptor is that a “protocol” implies a set list of steps to carry out that are known to be effective. Yet truly valuable protocols also allow for flexibility, so that you can apply and adapt each protocol to your specific circumstances and needs. -Understanding the mechanisms behind  protocols that allow them to work is also incredibly powerful because it informs you which aspect of the protocols are flexible and which are not. -The main reason to have protocols for sleep, for waking and getting sunlight, for stress management, focus, exercise, nutrition etc. is NOT to be rigid or robotic but because **the human brain is incredibly prone to distraction and to allowing emotional states and circumstances take us off course from our goals.**-Having a certain number of protocols that we adhere to as often as possible, thus not only allows for increased productivity, but also opens up free time and the opportunity for spontaneity and relaxation, in ways that exceed if we simply “freestyle” everything.-The mighty @jockowillink describes this as “discipline equals freedom” and I couldn’t agree more. -You can find Science Based Protocols for everything from sleep to focus to learning to exercise, deliberate heat and cold exposure and more in our zero cost Huberman Lab podcast newsletter- simply go to hubermanlab.com and go to the menu tab and then scroll to newsletter and then sign up with your email. It covers a diverse range of topics, including what sorts of music are most effective at shifting our mood, or at helping us move through sadness, what music has been shown to elevate dopamine levels or relieve anxiety, and more.-I also discuss how we have dedicated neural circuits in the brain for music perception, and that music is likely the most fundamental form of vocal language. It’s also very clear that children who learn a musical instrument have different brain connectivity than children who do not, and that music playing children can use those neural connections to better learn other types of information throughout life. -I also describe the research exploring how listening to music can impact our ability to learn and whether to do these at the same time. The brief summary of that body of research is listed on the slide. Obviously, it’s not about learning music se; it’s about simultaneous learning with background music or music being played in headphones. -The Music  Your Brain episode ought to be of interest to anyone who is a musician or who simply enjoys listening to music, and/or is interested in learning and brain plasticity.-You can find the full episode in all formats at hubermanlab.com. She explains what emotions are and how the brain represents and integrates signals from our body and the environment around us to create our unique emotional states. -We discuss the relationship between emotions and language, and how our specificity of language- indeed the very words we use, impact our emotional processing. -And we discuss the role of facial expressions in emotions, and how emotions relate to sleep, movement, nutrition and the building and reinforcement of social bonds. -We include a lot of actionable tools for how to regulate feelings of uncertainty and tools to better understand the emotional states of ourselves and others. -The episode ought to be of interest to anyone curious about the neuroscience and psychology underlying emotions and for those who seek to better understand themselves and relate to others and the world in richer, more adaptive ways.-You can find the episode in all formats at hubermanlab.com. We are lucky enough that life gives us a chance to rewrite our lives everyday. In case you’re looking at me today, here’s a reminder that you can rebuild yourself. Having better body composition whether you are underweight, or more to love, takes time; IT TAKES TIME. Most people who are overweight will under-eat and go from zero to hero on their workout journey; this mentality will ruin your relationship with food and movement. You’ll be binging feeling deprived from nutritious food that will serve as an energy source to power up your workouts, help you repair muscle, and lose body fat.On the other hand, someone who is underweight will not put on healthy weight in the form of more muscle mass with decreased body fat,if he/she is eating unhealthy/processed foods that have a high calorie content, but no nutritional value.It truly involves making a lifestyle change that is sustainable enough to help you be consistent. I didn’t starve. I didn’t waist train. I didn’t take any appetite suppressants. This is the result of a balanced nutrition program, consistency, proper supplementation, and HARD WORK! Postpartum Journey | Day 6*Cue identity crisis*Truth is I’m struggling hard today. Swipe for a video update on how I’m really feeling. These videos were from earlier this week when I felt a whole lot better. Adjusting to this new normal is a struggle. For the past 8 years my identity has been a full time CEO and I’m now trying to juggle that as well as a full time mum. I went “back to work” this week and it was not what I thought it would be. I’m solely breastfeeding so I’m with my baby all day and night trying to work and get stuff done when he is sleeping but this chunk likes to eat every 2 hours around the clock so there is not much time alone to get much done. Before I start, I am so grateful I get to do both so don’t get me wrong but that doesn’t change the challenge of it all. I have always worked hard so I can create the life I want. I do want this life… it’s just a hard adjustment for me today... tomorrow will likely be different (yay hormones) it’s a lot to wrap your mind around. I know it will get easier and I know there are so many incredible women out there doing both (*inspiring AF*). I think it’s important to share my struggles too. Postpartum isn’t easy. So if you’re going through it and feel alone… you’re not. My daily reminders are to ALWAYS practice gratitude for the freedom to have this struggle. To be patient with myself because it’s only been 7 weeks. To be fully present while my baby is awake. Not to take a moment for granted, even when he is crying and 💩 up to his neck. And as always… to surrender to the lack of control and take every day as it comes.Soon I will find a routine… I hope 🤞 In other news… I crushed this workout from the Daily SWEAT on my HEF Training App and it only took 30 minutes! 🙌🏽Available on HannahEdenFitness.com #HannahEdenFitness #PostpartumStruggles #Postpartum #HEFTraining #StrengthWorkout #Raw #Truth

The stuff they don’t tell you about in the books… I have been consciously taking care of myself. Showering, doing my hair and slapping some makeup on because it is making me feel better about myself as a whole… why you may ask yourself? Navigating motherhood and my new identity simultaneously is quite a task. I don’t recognize my body. My healing journey is quite a mind f$.k to be honest. I can’t move like I’m used to, getting in and out of bed is uncomfortable, sitting and walking is uncomfortable. This is the hardest part for me that I was not mentally ready for. Most of the time I am wearing my adult diapers, leaking from all different body parts, covered in baby pee or puke and I wouldn’t change it for the world. Waking every 60 minutes to two hours to feed my guy 24 hours a day(cluster feeding 😅🙌🏽) This is the part I don’t mind funnily enough! I spend a lot of time breastfeeding and pumping, I think I’m tired, but also the happiest I think I’ve ever been. I have a whole new appreciation for my mother and all mothers over the world. The duality of motherhood is a similar feeling I have had before. Everything all at once. Light and darkness. Hard but beautiful. Jagged and smooth. Peace amongst the chaos. It’s all a part of the process and somehow for me, it balances out to be more positive than negative. I’m so grateful Brixton chose us. It brings me comfort knowing that I am not alone. Billions of women have done this across the globe but I thought I would share the whole story of my introduction to motherhood to ensure that you didn’t think I look dolled up and happy 100% of the time. #Motherhood #NewMum #HannahEdenFitness

So much change in my life lately, like all of a sudden I’m Into Peppers™️. These are Jimmy Nardellos (sweet, not spicy) and a few of a variety I forget the name of, but are VERY HOT (spicy), split in half lengthwise, no seeds or stem removal because that’s not very me, is it? Drown them in olive oil (I’m using @zoegourmet, the same we carry for the bulk section @firstbloomcornerstore) season with salt, maybe pepper. Roast them in a shallow, lovely little oven safe vessel (baking dish, cast iron, skillet, braiser) at 325 until they’re perfectly blackened and deliciously caramelized at the edges, positively sizzling in their little hot tub of oil, 45-55 minutes. Add an onion or some crushed garlic cloves to roast with the peppers, or a handful of cumin or fennel seeds- all could be nice, but the peppers alone are sort of undeniably perfect. This is an Instagram caption not a work of fine art so unfortunately I am underselling them- but they are better than you think they possibly could be, I promise. Eat them alone or with whatever else you’re having for dinner, maybe a chicken, or layered with some fresh tomatoes in a little salad. They’re pretty rich and I don’t think they want any cheese, but I know someone out there is thinking of mozzarella, and that’s fine. Thank you @lanisfarm for growing these perfect peppers, I love your farm so much ☀️🌶️

I decided to be fancy and take my family to try the very hip and stylish W Goa this time. Here’s my review and why I feel it’s unique- 1. Location: It’s on top of a hill overlooking the sea in Vagator. 2. Design: Bold colours, lots of modern art. 3. Rooms: Very unusual rooms with chandeliers and bright colours, bathtubs with TVs -reel coming soon 4. Service: Staff is very friendly and they are pretty quick. 5. Atmosphere: Young, modern, cool. 6. Reception area is called The Living Room and is very lively with music and parties and a bar. ( that’s the W brand, their receptions are all like nightclubs and they were especially famous in the early 2000s) 7. Food: Delicious especially the Asian Restaurant -Spice Traders and I loved the Goan Thaali in their coffee shop. ( pls note the thaali is HUGE, 4 people can eat from it :) 8. Their “Rock Pool” is one of the most famous pools in Goa. Unfortunately the Rock Pool isn’t working right now, it will be ready for the season. 9. They have an indoor adults only pool in their spa which is dimly lit with candles all around it. Their spa has a lot of interesting options. I haven’t tried it yet, will do later today. #WGoa  #goahotels @w_goa
